'''Charles Samuel Joelson''' ([[January 27]], [[1916]] - [[August 17]], [[1999]]) was an [[United States|American]] [[lawyer]] and [[Politics of the United States|politician]]. Joelson, a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], succeeded [[Gordon Canfield]] as the  [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 8th congressional district|New Jersey's 8th District]] for eight years, lasting from [[1961]] until his resignation on [[September 4]], [[1969]], when he became a judge in the [[New Jersey Superior Court|Superior Court]] of [[New Jersey]].<ref name="House">{{cite web
 | title = Charles Samuel Joelson Profile
  | publisher = [[United States Congress]]
  | author = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=J000108
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref>

==Background==
Joelson was born and raised in a [[Jew]]ish family in [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref name="Pol">{{cite web
 | title = Charles S. Joelson Info
  | publisher = [[The Political Graveyard]]
  | author = [[Lawrence Kestenbaum]]
  | date = 
  | url = http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/jex-johansen.html
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref> After graduating from [[Montclair Kimberley Academy|Montclair Academy]], he went on to college and attended [[Cornell University]].<ref name="House"/> After graduating [[Phi Beta Kappa]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[1937]],<ref name="Tribute">{{cite web
 | title = Charles Samuel Joelson Tribute
  | publisher = [[The Library of Congress]]
  | author = [[Bill Pascrell Jr.]]
  | date = 
  | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?r106:14:./temp/~r106MnVgZc::
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref>  Joelson went to attend the university's [[Cornell Law School|law school]]. He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree in [[1939]], and was admitted to the bar in [[1940]].<ref name="House"/> He first started his [[practice of law|law practice]] in [[Paterson, New Jersey]] and continued until he enlisted in the [[United States Navy]] in [[1942]].<ref name="House"/> During [[World War II]], Joelson served as an ensign in the Far Eastern Branch of the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]], where he learned and mastered the [[Japanese language]].<ref name="Tribute"/> After the war, Joelson first ran for the House seat in [[New Jersey's 8th congressional district]] against incumbent [[Gordon Canfield]]. In a close election, Canfield captured 59,191 votes, just 148 more than Joelson, and was proclaimed the winner of the election.<ref>{{cite book |editor=John L. Moore |others= |title=Congressional Quarterly's Guide to U.S. Elections|edition= 3rd |year= 1994 |publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]]  |id=0-87187-996-4 |pages=1543}} pg. 1211</ref> Joelson then served on [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]]'s city counsel from [[1949]] to [[1952]].<ref name="House"/> 

==Politics and Superior Court==
He then served as deputy [[State Attorney General|Attorney General]] in [[New Jersey]]'s criminal investigation division for three years, starting in [[1954]]. That same year, he again ran for the [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] seat for [[United States Congressional Delegations from New Jersey|New Jersey's 8th District]], but again lost to [[incumbent]] [[Gordon Canfield]].<ref>{{cite web
 | title = US Representatives for New Jersey in the 1950s
  | publisher = [[The Political Graveyard]]
  | author = [[Lawrence Kestenbaum]]
  | date = 
  | url = http://politicalgraveyard.com/geo/NJ/ofc/usrep1950s.html
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref> Joelson received 45.1% of the vote, in comparison to Canfield's 54.8%.<ref>Moore (1994), pg. 1226</ref> Afterwards, Joelson then went on to the [[Passaic County]]'s Prosecutorâ€™s Office and then became the director of the state's criminal investigation division and served that post from [[1958]] to [[1960]].<ref name="House"/> 

He won the seat for [[New Jersey's 8th congressional district|New Jersey's 8th District]]'s in the November 1960 election. Canfield was not a candidate for renomination in [[1960]], and so Joelson was pitted against Republican Walter P. Kennedy. Joelson won the election by nearly 14,000 votes, capturing a 52%-43.8% majority.<ref>Moore (1994), pg. 1241</ref> He was sworn into the [[United States Congress]] on [[January 3]], [[1961]]. As Congressman, one of Joelson's finest achievements was a piece of legislation in [[1969]] that saved many school libraries. The legislation appropriated over a billion dollars for public school libraries, remedial programs and guidance counseling.<ref name="Tribute"/>

After his resignation, then-state cabinet member [[Robert A. Roe]] was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] by special election on [[November 4]], [[1969]] to fill the vacancy left by Joelson.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Robert A. Roe Profile
  | publisher = [[United States Congress]]
  | author = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000383
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
 | title = Ninety-First Congress: January 3, 1969, to January 3, 1971
  | publisher = [[United States Congress]]
  | author = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://a257.g.akamaitech.net/7/257/2422/26jan20061725/www.gpoaccess.gov/serialset/cdocuments/hd108-222/91st.pdf
  | accessdate = 2006-12-26 }}</ref> Joelson had asked the state's governor at the time, [[Richard J. Hughes]] for a seat in the [[New Jersey Superior Court]].<ref name="Tribute"/> He served on the bench for fifteen years, spending time in the [[New Jersey Superior Court#Chancery Division|Chancery Division]] and the [[New Jersey Superior Court#Appellate Division|Appellate Division]], before retiring in [[1984]].<ref name="Tribute"/>

Joelson died at the age of 83 in [[Freehold, New Jersey]]<ref name="Pol"/> on [[August 17]], [[1999]].<ref name="House"/>
 
